00:08:04.340 --> 00:08:07.950
Here's the arrows that
come over the wing.

00:08:07.950 --> 00:08:10.260
And then what ends up
happening is, really

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:13.440
what you care about is
the air that's going over

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:16.660
top of the wing, that's normal
to the chord line of the wing

00:08:16.660 --> 00:08:17.160
itself.

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:18.960
You know what I mean
when I say chord?

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:20.230
Just like this imaginary line.

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:23.310
So on a Hershey bar wing,
all of that air hits the wing

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:25.920
and it goes directly over top
of that chord line of the wing.

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:28.260
So like when we talked
about over here,

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:29.790
the wings have camber.

00:08:29.790 --> 00:08:33.000
So what happens to the air as
it goes over top of any wing?

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.299
Doesn't matter if it's a
fighter wing or whatever else.

00:08:35.299 --> 00:08:38.490
But what happens to the velocity
of the air as it goes over top?

00:08:38.490 --> 00:08:40.150
It goes faster, right.

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:42.640
So if I'm already going
fast and air hits my wing

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:45.220
and goes over top of
my wing and goes faster

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:47.160
than the rest of
the airplane, that's

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:49.950
going to cause a problem when
you get to very high speeds

00:08:49.950 --> 00:08:52.330
approaching Mach because what
ends up happening is you'll

00:08:52.330 --> 00:08:54.250
get a shockwave
forming on that wing.

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:56.590
And the moment you get a
shockwave form in there, that's

00:08:56.590 --> 00:08:59.710
like a big brick
wall to the wind

00:08:59.710 --> 00:09:01.690
and that causes all
types of drag downstream,

00:09:01.690 --> 00:09:03.800
slows down the airplane,
all types of things.

00:09:03.800 --> 00:09:05.920
So what they found is
I can sweep the wing.

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:08.560
When I sweep the
wing, some of that air

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:09.790
is normal to the chord line.

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:12.160
So if this is the fuselage
over here, and here's the wing

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:14.420
and it comes back over
here, some of that air

00:09:14.420 --> 00:09:16.330
is going to be that way,
and some of that air

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:20.020
is going to actually go out
and go span-wise, if you will,

00:09:20.020 --> 00:09:20.710
like this.

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:22.210
So I'm trying to
draw this correctly

00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:23.850
to get the right angles.

00:09:23.850 --> 00:09:25.340
But you get my point.

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:27.680
So some of that
air goes span-wise.

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:29.230
Some of the reasons
why you have wing

00:09:29.230 --> 00:09:31.410
winglets, right, to prevent
some of that drag that

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:32.410
happens at the winglets.

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:33.610
But then also what
you're worried about

00:09:33.610 --> 00:09:35.680
is rather than the full
component of this wind,

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:37.450
you're only worried
about the wind

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:40.510
that's normal to the flow of the
way the chord line is set up.

00:09:40.510 --> 00:09:42.190
So that's why they
sweep the wings.

