00:19:32.540 --> 00:19:33.510
That's good.

00:19:33.510 --> 00:19:35.700
And this airplane--
this airplane has what?

00:19:35.700 --> 00:19:37.020
Ailerons, right.

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:39.750
So if I want to go right
and I move the yoke right,

00:19:39.750 --> 00:19:42.690
what happens to the ailerons
here in this airplane?

00:19:42.690 --> 00:19:43.860
Sorry, I'll put it that way.

00:19:43.860 --> 00:19:45.020
That way, you're setting up.

00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:45.970
So I'm going this way.

00:19:45.970 --> 00:19:47.610
So this aileron is doing what?

00:19:47.610 --> 00:19:48.360
AUDIENCE: It's going that way.

00:19:48.360 --> 00:19:49.140
RANDY GORDON: Going
that way, right.

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:50.280
This aileron is doing what?

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:50.850
AUDIENCE: Up.

00:19:50.850 --> 00:19:53.490
RANDY GORDON: Up, right.

00:19:53.490 --> 00:19:55.170
So I'll cut to the chase.

00:19:55.170 --> 00:19:57.270
These are ailerons, these are--

00:19:57.270 --> 00:19:59.530
so these are the flaperons
here on the inside.

00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:01.830
These are the ailerons.

00:20:01.830 --> 00:20:05.560
In a Raptor, those aileron
deflect differentially.

00:20:05.560 --> 00:20:07.140
So just like you
have in a Cessna,

00:20:07.140 --> 00:20:09.750
they can also both
deflect up, they

00:20:09.750 --> 00:20:12.300
can also both deflect down.

00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:16.500
The flaps on the inboard are
flaps and ailerons-- flaperons.

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:19.560
So they can deflect up
and they can deflect down.

00:20:19.560 --> 00:20:22.090
We'll show why that
brings up some neat stuff.

00:20:22.090 --> 00:20:22.860
OK.

00:20:22.860 --> 00:20:25.680
Rudder, obviously back here.

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:28.170
In this airplane, when
I push the rudder left,

00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:30.690
the rudder deflects
left, I deflect right.

00:20:30.690 --> 00:20:32.430
This has two rudders.

00:20:32.430 --> 00:20:34.050
Both rudders can
deflect one way,

00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:35.370
they can deflect the other way.

00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:37.770
They can both deflect in,
and there's some reasons

00:20:37.770 --> 00:20:39.060
why you'd want to do that.

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:42.240
And they can both deflect out.

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:44.800
The last piece I'll
give you is back here,

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:46.590
normally this would
be called an elevator,

00:20:46.590 --> 00:20:48.540
but on a supersonic
airplane we call

00:20:48.540 --> 00:20:51.170
these horizontal stabilizers.

00:20:51.170 --> 00:20:53.880
If you guys have read the
story of the Bell X-1,

00:20:53.880 --> 00:20:56.310
so Chuck Yeager when
he went supersonic--

00:20:56.310 --> 00:20:58.730
we talked a little bit earlier
about supersonic shockwaves

00:20:58.730 --> 00:21:01.500
forming on the airplane
as you start going fast.

00:21:01.500 --> 00:21:04.200
What Chuck Yeager discovered
is that the elevator,

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:08.280
like in a traditional Cessna,
that horizontal stabilizer

00:21:08.280 --> 00:21:09.480
does not move.

00:21:09.480 --> 00:21:11.970
So the elevator
at the back moves,

00:21:11.970 --> 00:21:15.050
but this part stays fixed.

00:21:15.050 --> 00:21:17.550
That shockwave that
would form right here

00:21:17.550 --> 00:21:20.940
would actually blank the
air back to the elevator,

00:21:20.940 --> 00:21:22.640
and they wouldn't have
any pitch control.

00:21:22.640 --> 00:21:24.810
So when they talk about
this thing called Mach tuck,

00:21:24.810 --> 00:21:26.340
which was a scary,
scary thing that

00:21:26.340 --> 00:21:28.980
happened to a lot of World
War II fighter pilots when

00:21:28.980 --> 00:21:30.500
they got into a dive--

00:21:30.500 --> 00:21:32.670
they would start forming
shockwaves on the airplane.

00:21:32.670 --> 00:21:34.920
They didn't have the elevator
authority to pull up,

00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:36.810
and so they would actually
nose dive all the way in

00:21:36.810 --> 00:21:39.220
because they go faster and
faster and faster heading down.

00:21:39.220 --> 00:21:42.180
The answer was rather
than the back end

00:21:42.180 --> 00:21:46.170
of this thing maneuvering,
the entire surface moves.

00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:48.000
So as a fighter
pilot, especially

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:50.130
when you got people walking
underneath the airplane

00:21:50.130 --> 00:21:52.500
because they're maintainers,
they're working on things,

00:21:52.500 --> 00:21:54.880
you always, always, always,
you show them your hands.

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:56.990
Because if you tap
that stick, again,

00:21:56.990 --> 00:21:59.160
the stick is not directly
connected just like it is,

00:21:59.160 --> 00:22:00.790
the stick's connected
to a computer.

00:22:00.790 --> 00:22:02.880
The computer votes and it
allows things to happen.

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:06.330
It then commands a 4,000
hydraulic psi system to deflect

00:22:06.330 --> 00:22:07.500
basically this big old wing.

00:22:07.500 --> 00:22:09.490
You can actually
take a guy's head off

00:22:09.490 --> 00:22:10.870
with the flight
control surfaces.

00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:12.270
So you always, always
show your hands

00:22:12.270 --> 00:22:14.600
whenever you have people
walking underneath the airplane

00:22:14.600 --> 00:22:15.360
for that.

00:22:15.360 --> 00:22:17.880
So it's got a very, very
advanced flight control

00:22:17.880 --> 00:22:18.690
system on board.

00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:20.440
We'll talk through a
little bit about what

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:22.330
advantages that gives you.

00:22:22.330 --> 00:22:25.230
The last piece I'll
give you is the engines

00:22:25.230 --> 00:22:28.590
at the back, which
are a thing of beauty.

00:22:28.590 --> 00:22:30.270
I was a propulsion
guy, aeronautics

00:22:30.270 --> 00:22:32.590
engineer kind of thing.

00:22:32.590 --> 00:22:35.250
It's almost like modern
art masterpiece to me.

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:38.160
Those engines have
the ability to call

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:39.690
what's called thrust vectoring.

00:22:39.690 --> 00:22:42.690
They'll swing up and
they'll swing down.

00:22:42.690 --> 00:22:44.620
Where would you
want to use that?

00:22:44.620 --> 00:22:47.520
Why do the engines
have thrust vectoring?

00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:49.020
You've answered a lot today.

00:22:49.020 --> 00:22:49.470
You're smart, though.

00:22:49.470 --> 00:22:50.510
You know what's going on.

00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:51.360
Go ahead.

00:22:51.360 --> 00:22:52.560
AUDIENCE: Very low speeds.

00:22:52.560 --> 00:22:53.200
RANDY GORDON: Very low speeds.

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:54.250
Outstanding, yep.

00:22:54.250 --> 00:22:55.770
Where's another regime?

00:22:55.770 --> 00:22:59.070
Think of the flight
envelope of the airplane.

00:22:59.070 --> 00:23:00.530
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
very high altitude.

00:23:00.530 --> 00:23:01.900
RANDY GORDON: Very
high altitude.

00:23:01.900 --> 00:23:04.280
So why high altitudes?

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:06.450
AUDIENCE: A little lift
from the wings, or the wings

00:23:06.450 --> 00:23:07.630
could be small so--

00:23:07.630 --> 00:23:08.680
RANDY GORDON: Yeah, yeah.

00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:11.530
Density goes way down as
you go up in altitude.

00:23:11.530 --> 00:23:12.460
So if I deflect--

00:23:12.460 --> 00:23:14.110
I mean, I have to
get more deflection

00:23:14.110 --> 00:23:17.110
to move that air to be able
to move the airplane if I'm

00:23:17.110 --> 00:23:19.690
relying just on the
aerosurfaces alone.

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:23.590
The way I get around that is
I put two 35,000 thrust pound

00:23:23.590 --> 00:23:25.900
engines, if you will,
on board the airplane.

00:23:25.900 --> 00:23:28.660
And just like a fire hose, if I
grab a fire hose and I move it,

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:31.330
you would feel that torque
on your body, the same thing

00:23:31.330 --> 00:23:34.570
here with the thrust
vectoring on the back.

00:23:34.570 --> 00:23:36.490
So with just the
movement of my hand,

00:23:36.490 --> 00:23:39.530
I can deflect 70,000
pounds of thrust way

00:23:39.530 --> 00:23:40.870
at the back end of the airplane.

00:23:40.870 --> 00:23:44.500
So we talked about center of
gravity being right about here.

00:23:44.500 --> 00:23:46.590
So that moment arm
of that thrust force

00:23:46.590 --> 00:23:48.760
is all the way back here,
and I can deflect that up.

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:51.940
And at very, very low speeds,
where the flight control

00:23:51.940 --> 00:23:53.860
surfaces might
not be doing well,

00:23:53.860 --> 00:23:57.970
I can still move the airplane
just by using the thrust alone.

00:23:57.970 --> 00:23:59.500
At high altitude,
where I don't have

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:02.200
a lot of density, same thing,
I can maneuver the airplane

00:24:02.200 --> 00:24:04.770
just by using the thrust alone.

00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:06.010
So where that helps you--

00:24:06.010 --> 00:24:08.260
because, again, this
is a dog fighter.

00:24:08.260 --> 00:24:10.720
Here's what happens, and you'll
see this from time to time.

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:12.760
So I'll do this
with a side look.

00:24:12.760 --> 00:24:14.410
When I get to high
angle of attack,

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:16.750
so the wind is coming
like this and it's

00:24:16.750 --> 00:24:19.780
hitting the bottom
surface of the airplane,

00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:21.580
I don't have the ability
to really maneuver

00:24:21.580 --> 00:24:24.880
a lot because sometimes some
aerosurfaces are blanked

00:24:24.880 --> 00:24:27.460
by just the size of
that fuselage coming

00:24:27.460 --> 00:24:28.630
right out into the wing.

00:24:28.630 --> 00:24:31.540
So I cheat, if you will,
by using the engines to get

00:24:31.540 --> 00:24:33.220
that final little pitch rate.

00:24:33.220 --> 00:24:35.350
We'll see later on in
the Raptor demo video

00:24:35.350 --> 00:24:36.700
where the airplane will go--

00:24:36.700 --> 00:24:39.890
it's called a high alpha loop,
high angle of attack loop.

00:24:39.890 --> 00:24:43.090
It'll go vertical-- rather
than doing a loop where

00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:46.000
you see it prescribed
this whole path over here,

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:47.290
the airplane will go vertical.

00:24:47.290 --> 00:24:49.710
I'll engage the thrust
vectoring, and it'll pivot.

00:24:49.710 --> 00:24:51.880
So the velocity vector is
still heading straight up,

00:24:51.880 --> 00:24:53.530
so the airplane is
still moving up.

00:24:53.530 --> 00:24:56.170
But it kind of does
this gymnastics thing

00:24:56.170 --> 00:24:58.120
where I've now turned
the airplane using thrust

00:24:58.120 --> 00:24:59.960
vectoring, even though
the airplane is still

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:00.870
heading straight up.

00:25:00.870 --> 00:25:02.400
It's wacky.

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:03.280
It's totally cool.

00:25:06.790 --> 00:25:07.290
All right.

00:25:07.290 --> 00:25:09.260
Let's talk through a
couple other things.

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:09.760
OK.

00:25:09.760 --> 00:25:10.970
So that's the flight controls.

00:25:10.970 --> 00:25:11.850
How we do in timeline?

