OK.

00:25:12.030 --> 00:25:13.110
We're looking pretty good.

00:25:15.480 --> 00:25:20.460
Anyone recognize the
cockpit on your left?

00:25:20.460 --> 00:25:21.090
AUDIENCE: F-15.

00:25:21.090 --> 00:25:22.200
RANDY GORDON: F-15, yeah.

00:25:22.200 --> 00:25:22.890
Outstanding.

00:25:22.890 --> 00:25:23.850
Good.

00:25:23.850 --> 00:25:25.680
This was my very first airplane.

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:26.850
I didn't know any better.

00:25:26.850 --> 00:25:28.920
I sat down I said, wow,
what a cool cockpit.

00:25:28.920 --> 00:25:30.090
Look at all this cool stuff.

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:33.640
Buttons everywhere and
switches all over the place.

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:37.920
This is an airplane of the '70s,
designed when Richard Nixon,

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:41.460
Jimmy Carter, that kind
of era, if you will--

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:45.030
very, very first intro to
solid state electronics.

00:25:45.030 --> 00:25:47.700
Really wasn't fully
fleshed out at this stage.

00:25:47.700 --> 00:25:49.890
This airplane had a
hydro mechanical system,

00:25:49.890 --> 00:25:51.690
which meant that just
like in this airplane

00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:54.420
where there were cables
and pulleys, a similar kind

00:25:54.420 --> 00:25:57.260
of flight control
system in it there.

00:25:57.260 --> 00:26:00.720
This picture is the Raptor's
cockpit on the inside.

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:02.950
Some pretty dramatic
differences between the two.

00:26:02.950 --> 00:26:04.160
So again, just call them out.

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:06.260
What do you see?

00:26:06.260 --> 00:26:07.460
AUDIENCE: Glass cockpit.

00:26:07.460 --> 00:26:08.180
RANDY GORDON: Glass cockpit.

00:26:08.180 --> 00:26:09.220
Where does that help you?

00:26:11.610 --> 00:26:14.240
AUDIENCE: I say the
glass is cooler.

00:26:14.240 --> 00:26:15.200
RANDY GORDON: Go ahead.

00:26:15.200 --> 00:26:16.330
AUDIENCE: It can be display.

00:26:16.330 --> 00:26:17.200
RANDY GORDON: What's up?

00:26:17.200 --> 00:26:18.010
AUDIENCE: It can
be multi-display.

00:26:18.010 --> 00:26:19.000
You can change it to--

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:19.960
RANDY GORDON: Oh, yeah.

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:20.710
It's great.

00:26:20.710 --> 00:26:23.380
You can see these new
digital cockpit Mercedes Benz

00:26:23.380 --> 00:26:25.690
and BMWs or whatever,
where in the old days

00:26:25.690 --> 00:26:27.790
you just had speed
and tack, if you will.

00:26:27.790 --> 00:26:30.610
Now you can configure
it however you want.

00:26:30.610 --> 00:26:34.530
Now, the moment you start
putting that in there--

00:26:34.530 --> 00:26:35.470
no, got it.

00:26:35.470 --> 00:26:37.050
Yeah, the moment you
start doing stuff

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:40.410
like that, you start creating
a software airplane, which

00:26:40.410 --> 00:26:42.600
gives you a lot of
flexibility and a danger.

00:26:42.600 --> 00:26:44.600
We'll talk about that one
a little bit later on.

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:49.540
What else do you see
flight controls-wise

00:26:49.540 --> 00:26:51.960
since we're talking mainly
about flight controls today?

00:26:51.960 --> 00:26:52.840
AUDIENCE: Side stick.

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:54.570
RANDY GORDON: Side stick, yeah.

00:26:54.570 --> 00:27:01.110
So right there is the
control stick in an F-15.

00:27:01.110 --> 00:27:03.330
Sits directly
between your knees.

00:27:03.330 --> 00:27:07.390
In a Raptor, that is
your control stick.

00:27:07.390 --> 00:27:09.000
It's on the side.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:10.700
Why would you ever
want to put something

00:27:10.700 --> 00:27:11.620
like that on the side?

00:27:11.620 --> 00:27:12.120
Go ahead.

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:13.600
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:13.600 --> 00:27:14.940
RANDY GORDON: That's part of it.

00:27:14.940 --> 00:27:15.440
That helps.

00:27:15.440 --> 00:27:17.100
And there's actually--
you can't see it.

00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:19.530
Here it's partly there, but
this little section here, it's

00:27:19.530 --> 00:27:21.150
a foldout armrest.

00:27:21.150 --> 00:27:23.310
So your wrist is on the stick.

00:27:23.310 --> 00:27:26.040
Your elbow, if you will,
it's resting on an arm rest.

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:28.110
So it gives you a lot
of leverage from there.

00:27:28.110 --> 00:27:28.890
That's one reason.

00:27:28.890 --> 00:27:30.390
What's a couple
other reasons why

00:27:30.390 --> 00:27:32.580
you'd want to go side
stick versus center stick?

00:27:32.580 --> 00:27:33.960
AUDIENCE: Your legs get in
the way on the center stick.

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:35.370
RANDY GORDON: Legs
get in the way.

00:27:35.370 --> 00:27:38.700
That's a big deal
because in this airplane,

00:27:38.700 --> 00:27:40.950
you actually got pretty good
after while of flying it,

00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:42.500
where if you really need
to maneuver the stick,

00:27:42.500 --> 00:27:44.340
you kind of do the leg
up and kind of move

00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:46.470
over that way to get
everything out of the way.

00:27:46.470 --> 00:27:49.090
The other side about it, too, it
might not be quite so obvious,

00:27:49.090 --> 00:27:50.310
but you see how that stick--

00:27:50.310 --> 00:27:52.330
that's about where your
eye height would be.

00:27:52.330 --> 00:27:53.790
You see how that
stick kind of gets

00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:56.730
in the way of seeing
some of the instruments?

00:27:56.730 --> 00:27:58.040
It's just sitting right there.

00:27:58.040 --> 00:28:00.900
In a side stick, that's
completely off to the side

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:04.590
and all of this real
estate is completely open.

00:28:04.590 --> 00:28:07.680
The other thing I'll give you,
again, just for sake of time,

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:10.590
it's a little bit
of a thought change.

00:28:10.590 --> 00:28:15.160
When you have a
center stick, it's

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:17.000
like when you're driving a car.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.310
And when you're parking--

00:28:19.310 --> 00:28:20.770
you're trying to
park your car, you

00:28:20.770 --> 00:28:24.360
want to be able to maneuver
that wheel around a lot.

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:25.780
But when you're
at highway speeds,

00:28:25.780 --> 00:28:27.650
if you were to take the
wheel and maneuver it

00:28:27.650 --> 00:28:30.280
that much again, you're
going to roll the car.

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:35.950
So in a center stick,
you move the stick around

00:28:35.950 --> 00:28:38.210
to be able to deflect the
flight control surfaces.

00:28:38.210 --> 00:28:40.210
There's a physical
displacement of the stick

00:28:40.210 --> 00:28:41.500
to make that happen.

00:28:41.500 --> 00:28:44.830
On a side stick, that stick,
initially when they first

00:28:44.830 --> 00:28:48.220
put it in, did not move at all.

00:28:48.220 --> 00:28:50.990
So imagine if you were in your
car and you wanted to steer,

00:28:50.990 --> 00:28:52.930
and rather than the
wheel actually moving,

00:28:52.930 --> 00:28:55.270
you just put pressure
on the wheel itself

00:28:55.270 --> 00:28:58.120
and that was enough to transmit
to the computer in the car

00:28:58.120 --> 00:28:59.860
to turn the wheels.

00:28:59.860 --> 00:29:03.310
That was a problem initially,
which we can talk about

00:29:03.310 --> 00:29:04.270
after the presentation.

00:29:04.270 --> 00:29:06.130
That's a little bit of
a sidebar discussion.

00:29:06.130 --> 00:29:08.020
This is a human factors thing.

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:09.190
It's a side stick.

00:29:09.190 --> 00:29:10.510
Initially it didn't move.

00:29:10.510 --> 00:29:13.070
Eventually they decided,
I'll put in some deflection.

00:29:13.070 --> 00:29:15.730
So I can go a half inch
left, a half inch right,

00:29:15.730 --> 00:29:20.340
about a quarter inch forward,
I go about a half inch back

00:29:20.340 --> 00:29:22.930
because normally I really want
to get the nose going this way.

00:29:22.930 --> 00:29:24.510
If I had that much
deflection forward,

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:26.410
I don't want to fly
the airplane this way.

00:29:26.410 --> 00:29:28.170
So you have the
ability to do that.

00:29:28.170 --> 00:29:30.550
But it gives you a little bit
of the best of both worlds.

00:29:30.550 --> 00:29:32.140
There's some
deflection to give you

00:29:32.140 --> 00:29:34.810
feedback that you've input
something on the stick,

00:29:34.810 --> 00:29:36.230
but not so much
deflection that it

00:29:36.230 --> 00:29:38.530
gets in the way of everything
else you're trying to do.

00:29:38.530 --> 00:29:41.470
So there's a little bit of real
estate in the fighter cockpit.

00:29:41.470 --> 00:29:43.590
The last piece I'll give
you, and it's a little bit

00:29:43.590 --> 00:29:49.960
hard to see here, is all those
buttons there on the stick.

00:29:49.960 --> 00:29:51.670
What you have the
ability to do-- so

00:29:51.670 --> 00:29:55.540
it's exactly like modern car
steering wheels right now.

00:29:55.540 --> 00:29:58.270
You can control volume, radio,
everything else like that,

00:29:58.270 --> 00:30:00.010
you can do it from
the steering wheel.

00:30:00.010 --> 00:30:01.090
Same thing in a fighter.

00:30:01.090 --> 00:30:03.450
It's called hands-on
throttle and stick, HOTAS.

00:30:03.450 --> 00:30:05.080
And it allows you to
control everything

00:30:05.080 --> 00:30:06.780
that you would want
to do on the airplane

00:30:06.780 --> 00:30:09.430
with never having
to leave your hands

00:30:09.430 --> 00:30:11.380
from the throttle on the stick.

00:30:11.380 --> 00:30:13.540
The other piece I'll give
you is that in a Raptor--

00:30:13.540 --> 00:30:16.060
so in a fighter like
this, this is your stick,

00:30:16.060 --> 00:30:17.280
this is your throttle.

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:19.480
In a Raptor, because
the flight control modes

00:30:19.480 --> 00:30:22.540
can change so much, this
is your right inceptor

00:30:22.540 --> 00:30:25.180
and this is your left inceptor.

00:30:25.180 --> 00:30:28.130
It's all considered part of
the flight control system.

00:30:28.130 --> 00:30:28.630
All right.

00:30:28.630 --> 00:30:31.200
Let's keep going.

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:35.690
So just like on your car where
if you want to go to XM radio,

00:30:35.690 --> 00:30:38.630
you go to media
source or whatever

00:30:38.630 --> 00:30:41.720
and go XM satellite
radio, you have buttons

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:44.990
because it's a software-driven
jet, just like we saw before,

00:30:44.990 --> 00:30:47.390
and I can pull up a flight
control display that

00:30:47.390 --> 00:30:50.130
shows me the position of all
my flight control surfaces.

00:30:50.130 --> 00:30:54.020
Again, the pilot is way
forward on the front end

00:30:54.020 --> 00:30:54.740
of this airplane.

00:30:54.740 --> 00:30:58.160
As I deflect things, sometimes
I can't actually see them.

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:00.310
And so initially, this
was a flight test display

00:31:00.310 --> 00:31:02.480
so that I don't have to do
the old poltergeist thing

00:31:02.480 --> 00:31:03.980
and try to rotate
all the way around

00:31:03.980 --> 00:31:06.140
to be able to see to the
back end of the airplane

00:31:06.140 --> 00:31:07.940
to see if the elevators moving.

00:31:07.940 --> 00:31:09.860
I basically instrument
everything and I

00:31:09.860 --> 00:31:10.880
can see it here.

00:31:10.880 --> 00:31:12.590
Now, some of the
human factor stuff

00:31:12.590 --> 00:31:14.510
that's kind of cool
with how they did this--

00:31:17.950 --> 00:31:20.730
so again, this tells you, at
the top, rudder deflection

00:31:20.730 --> 00:31:24.270
surfaces, ailerons, where the
horizontal stabilizers are at,

00:31:24.270 --> 00:31:25.680
how the engines are doing.

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:27.070
This is a little weird.

00:31:27.070 --> 00:31:28.380
I don't really like
how they did this one,

00:31:28.380 --> 00:31:30.750
but this is the leading edge
flaps, LE flaps, the leading

00:31:30.750 --> 00:31:31.180
edge flaps.

00:31:31.180 --> 00:31:33.470
So it just shows you how far
they're deflected, dug in,

00:31:33.470 --> 00:31:35.100
dug down.

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:38.680
On the lower left-hand corner,
it shows you center of gravity.

00:31:38.680 --> 00:31:40.380
So there's limits.

00:31:40.380 --> 00:31:41.910
Just like what
you would normally

00:31:41.910 --> 00:31:43.670
do on flight planning
for your Cessna--

00:31:43.670 --> 00:31:46.020
hey, I can only put this much
fuel with this much passengers,

00:31:46.020 --> 00:31:47.760
and I've got to be within
this limit for takeoff,

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:50.430
for landing and everything else,
the airplane tells you that.

00:31:50.430 --> 00:31:52.470
Now, what's cool about
some of the things they've

00:31:52.470 --> 00:31:54.510
done in Raptor is that
if it's out of limits,

00:31:54.510 --> 00:31:56.490
again, it doesn't expect you
to get out the piece of paper

00:31:56.490 --> 00:31:58.050
with the whiz wheel and the E6B.

00:31:58.050 --> 00:31:59.550
It just changes color.

00:31:59.550 --> 00:32:03.840
It goes red and it gives you a
warning that says, hey, idiot,

00:32:03.840 --> 00:32:06.950
you are beyond the
aft center of gravity.

00:32:06.950 --> 00:32:08.910
No gauge tells you it's
just having a hard time

00:32:08.910 --> 00:32:10.380
seeing where all the fuel
is and everything else.

00:32:10.380 --> 00:32:11.530
That's a different story.

00:32:11.530 --> 00:32:15.270
But it tells you what percentage
of mean aerodynamic chord

00:32:15.270 --> 00:32:18.370
that you're sitting at and it's
able to adjust stuff around.

00:32:18.370 --> 00:32:21.570
So I'll give that to you
because what this allows is--

00:32:21.570 --> 00:32:23.820
oh, by the way, the last
part here is flight control--

00:32:23.820 --> 00:32:26.340
so in other words, this tells
you where you moved your stick

00:32:26.340 --> 00:32:27.470
and it tells you trim.

00:32:27.470 --> 00:32:28.890
So you know where
the trim is set,

00:32:28.890 --> 00:32:30.760
and it also tells you
where the stick is set.

00:32:30.760 --> 00:32:32.910
So you know your inputs
that go through there.

00:32:32.910 --> 00:32:35.220
When you have a
software-driven machine,

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:39.220
you can customize things
and make it very simple.

00:32:39.220 --> 00:32:41.760
You guys have seen that
terrible, terrible awful movie

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:42.700
Top Gun, right?

00:32:42.700 --> 00:32:44.190
It's just awful, right?

00:32:44.190 --> 00:32:46.960
So that scene where
Maverick loses his engines

00:32:46.960 --> 00:32:49.590
and they go through this, engine
one is out, engine two is out,

00:32:49.590 --> 00:32:52.950
and they go on this flat spin
to sea, which is a bunch of BS.

00:32:52.950 --> 00:32:55.710
When you're in a spin, you
don't translate over the ground,

00:32:55.710 --> 00:32:56.820
you fall straight down.

00:32:56.820 --> 00:32:59.200
So this whole flying out
to sea thing is ridiculous.

00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:00.330
It doesn't happen that way.

00:33:02.980 --> 00:33:04.860
If you don't have a
software-driven airplane,

00:33:04.860 --> 00:33:06.750
when you lose engines like that,
then you've got to go through

00:33:06.750 --> 00:33:07.560
this whole--

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:11.410
for instance, in the Cessna,
if you lose the motor,

00:33:11.410 --> 00:33:12.330
what do you got to do?

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:14.710
Establish your glide, get
everything set up, check to see

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:16.710
am I my left, right, or
both on the fuel source,

00:33:16.710 --> 00:33:19.410
what's my whatever, blah, blah,
blah, and everything else.

00:33:19.410 --> 00:33:21.660
In the Raptor it's the most
awesome thing possible,

00:33:21.660 --> 00:33:23.760
you literally do nothing.

00:33:23.760 --> 00:33:26.530
You sit there and the computer
goes, oh, you've lost a motor.

00:33:26.530 --> 00:33:28.160
I've noticed that
you have a problem.

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:30.210
Let me see if I can help
you, and it will restart

00:33:30.210 --> 00:33:31.750
the motor for you if it can.

00:33:31.750 --> 00:33:33.600
If it can't restart
the motor, chances

00:33:33.600 --> 00:33:36.150
are it ain't going to restart
and you can leave it shut down,

00:33:36.150 --> 00:33:37.290
if you will.

00:33:37.290 --> 00:33:39.900
It allows some neat
human factor designs

00:33:39.900 --> 00:33:42.700
because in this airplane-- in
the Raptor, believe it or not,

00:33:42.700 --> 00:33:44.250
when you're flying
the Raptor, you're

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:46.950
not thinking about
flying the Raptor.

00:33:46.950 --> 00:33:48.820
You're thinking about
employing the Raptor.

00:33:48.820 --> 00:33:51.030
So you're trying to find
where all of your wing mates

00:33:51.030 --> 00:33:54.180
are, where the bad guys
are, et cetera, et cetera.

00:33:54.180 --> 00:33:56.730
Flying is secondary.

00:33:56.730 --> 00:33:59.520
Whereas in this plane,
flying is everything.

00:33:59.520 --> 00:34:01.920
So they tried to
as much as possible

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:04.740
alleviate the pilot from as
much burden of responsibility

00:34:04.740 --> 00:34:06.750
of thinking about flying
the airplane by doing

00:34:06.750 --> 00:34:08.650
neat little tricks like that.

00:34:08.650 --> 00:34:11.100
The other thing I'll give you
too about the flight controls

00:34:11.100 --> 00:34:13.830
is, again, we talked about
how ailerons can go up,

00:34:13.830 --> 00:34:16.590
ailerons can come down,
flaperons go up, they go down,

00:34:16.590 --> 00:34:18.030
rudders come out and go down.

00:34:18.030 --> 00:34:21.880
On takeoff mode, I'll show
you something kind of cool.

00:34:21.880 --> 00:34:24.780
So here's the nose look on here.

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:26.760
On takeoff mode,
without any input

00:34:26.760 --> 00:34:29.790
from the pilot-- so there's
no flap switch in the cockpit,

00:34:29.790 --> 00:34:32.870
there's no leading edge,
there's nothing like that.

00:34:32.870 --> 00:34:34.710
It just knows, based
on the fact that you've

00:34:34.710 --> 00:34:37.190
got the gear handled down and
that you're on the ground,

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:39.150
that it senses the weight
on wheels, it thinks,

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:40.770
this guy wants to take off.

00:34:40.770 --> 00:34:44.210
So the rudders will
both deflect inward.

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:46.070
Why would you do that?

00:34:46.070 --> 00:34:46.570
Go ahead.

00:34:46.570 --> 00:34:50.440
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:34:55.550 --> 00:34:58.280
RANDY GORDON: So not quite.

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:00.400
There is a tie between the
flight controls, though.

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:02.070
So in other words,
if I take the rudders

00:35:02.070 --> 00:35:05.920
and I tow them both in, so
both rudders are deflected in,

00:35:05.920 --> 00:35:08.870
what does that do from an
aerodynamic standpoint?

00:35:08.870 --> 00:35:11.500
Which way's the nose going to go
if these rudders are deflected

00:35:11.500 --> 00:35:12.140
in?

00:35:12.140 --> 00:35:12.680
AUDIENCE: Up.

00:35:12.680 --> 00:35:14.230
RANDY GORDON: Up, right.

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:17.050
So it makes it easier to
rotate the airplane on takeoff

00:35:17.050 --> 00:35:19.210
because the rudders
are deflecting in.

00:35:19.210 --> 00:35:21.460
Both of them go in.

00:35:21.460 --> 00:35:23.290
The other part about it too is--

00:35:23.290 --> 00:35:24.400
so we talked about this.

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:26.710
You guys ever see a
competition aerobatic,

00:35:26.710 --> 00:35:29.190
one of those extra
300 kind of airplanes?

00:35:29.190 --> 00:35:31.450
See how the aileron
runs the entire length

00:35:31.450 --> 00:35:32.540
of the whole wing?

00:35:32.540 --> 00:35:34.750
So the pilot, all they got
to do is just tap the wing

00:35:34.750 --> 00:35:37.270
and the airplane is going to
do corkscrews and spirals.

00:35:37.270 --> 00:35:39.190
On a Raptor, that's
part of the reason

00:35:39.190 --> 00:35:41.650
why the aileron and the
flaperon can move together

00:35:41.650 --> 00:35:43.250
as one surface.

00:35:43.250 --> 00:35:45.760
And so the leading
edge flaps will dig in.

00:35:45.760 --> 00:35:48.640
The trailing aileron and
the trailing edge flap,

00:35:48.640 --> 00:35:50.420
that will dig in as well.

00:35:50.420 --> 00:35:55.120
So on takeoff, with no
input from the pilot,

00:35:55.120 --> 00:35:58.090
whereas the wing normally
would look like this

00:35:58.090 --> 00:36:01.330
with a little bit of
camber on it, on takeoff

00:36:01.330 --> 00:36:04.250
the wing looks like this.

00:36:04.250 --> 00:36:06.750
It's kind of cool like when
you look at from the side.

00:36:06.750 --> 00:36:09.890
So if you're looking at
it from directly side on,

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:12.650
that leading edge flap
comes down, these come down.

00:36:12.650 --> 00:36:16.040
That puts in a whole bunch
of camber on the wing,

00:36:16.040 --> 00:36:17.720
and it generates a lot of lift.

00:36:17.720 --> 00:36:19.970
And again, that's completely
independent of the pilot.

00:36:19.970 --> 00:36:22.640
The pilot has done nothing
other than just tell it,

00:36:22.640 --> 00:36:26.370
I'm on the ground because
the gear handle is down.

00:36:26.370 --> 00:36:29.520
PROFESSOR: Laz, what would
be a typical rotation speed?

00:36:29.520 --> 00:36:30.320
RANDY GORDON: Yeah.

00:36:30.320 --> 00:36:31.650
So that's a good question.

00:36:31.650 --> 00:36:33.570
What do you guys think?

00:36:33.570 --> 00:36:34.630
So I start on the runway.

00:36:34.630 --> 00:36:36.290
By the way, I need
8,000 feet of runway.

00:36:36.290 --> 00:36:40.000
This whole 2,500 feet is not
for a Raptor, unfortunately.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:40.890
8,000 feet of runway.

00:36:40.890 --> 00:36:42.940
But by the time I actually
get ready to pull back

00:36:42.940 --> 00:36:46.150
on that stick to rotate, how
fast do you think it's going?

00:36:50.540 --> 00:36:52.570
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:52.570 --> 00:36:53.700
RANDY GORDON: Little close.

00:36:53.700 --> 00:36:55.740
150 is the usual--

00:36:55.740 --> 00:36:57.330
so about take off--
which, by the way,

00:36:57.330 --> 00:37:02.220
this airplane is about
34, 35 tons on takeoff,

00:37:02.220 --> 00:37:06.600
compared to 2,500
pounds or whatever.

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:07.850
So it's a very heavy airplane.

00:37:07.850 --> 00:37:09.350
It's got to get a
lot of speed to be

00:37:09.350 --> 00:37:10.470
able to get that rotation.

00:37:10.470 --> 00:37:13.990
But it's about 150,
160 knots on takeoff,

00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:17.730
which is faster than the never
exceed speed of the Cessna,

00:37:17.730 --> 00:37:18.960
as it goes.

00:37:18.960 --> 00:37:21.420
But yeah, so the flight
controls are there to help you.

00:37:21.420 --> 00:37:22.800
The other thing
I'll show you too

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:25.380
is there is-- so
sailplane guys--

00:37:25.380 --> 00:37:26.550
where are my sailplane guys?

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:27.510
Anyone fly sailplanes?

00:37:27.510 --> 00:37:30.630
So on the left in a
sailplane cockpit,

00:37:30.630 --> 00:37:34.050
you typically have a lever for
the speed brakes, spoilers,

00:37:34.050 --> 00:37:36.450
so these big surfaces
that pop up on the wing

00:37:36.450 --> 00:37:38.580
to slow the airplane
down to just glide slopes

00:37:38.580 --> 00:37:39.720
and those sorts of things.

00:37:39.720 --> 00:37:41.220
We talked a little
bit earlier about

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:42.870
how the electrical
engineer guys want

00:37:42.870 --> 00:37:45.240
this thing to be completely
stealthy and whatever else.

00:37:45.240 --> 00:37:48.060
The last thing you want to do,
based on the discussion we just

00:37:48.060 --> 00:37:50.520
had, is I don't want to
have a big board stick up

00:37:50.520 --> 00:37:52.390
in the middle of this
airplane because that's

00:37:52.390 --> 00:37:54.700
going to make my radar
reflection go very, very large.

00:37:54.700 --> 00:37:56.400
So they did something
kind of remarkable.

00:37:56.400 --> 00:37:59.970
They used the flight
control surfaces themselves

00:37:59.970 --> 00:38:01.650
as the speed brakes.

00:38:01.650 --> 00:38:03.480
So if I need to slow
the airplane down,

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:05.250
I hit a little switch
on the throttle.

00:38:05.250 --> 00:38:08.640
And immediately what happens
is the leading edge flaps will

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:13.200
come down a bit, the
ailerons will both go up,

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:17.190
the rudders will go out,
so they'll both tow out.

00:38:17.190 --> 00:38:19.980
And it's using that to help
slow the airplane down.

00:38:19.980 --> 00:38:24.090
It's actually quite effective,
which is pretty cool.

00:38:24.090 --> 00:38:24.590
All right.

00:38:24.590 --> 00:38:27.110
A couple other things
we'll go through.

00:38:27.110 --> 00:38:29.500
Landing mode.

00:38:29.500 --> 00:38:30.700
Pilot's done nothing.

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:34.690
Touchdown, throttles are
back, gear handle's down,

00:38:34.690 --> 00:38:36.460
and all of this stuff happens.

00:38:36.460 --> 00:38:39.030
Here, let me get
this zoomed in here.

00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:40.770
So that's the aileron.

00:38:40.770 --> 00:38:41.730
It's up.

00:38:41.730 --> 00:38:42.600
Holy crap.

00:38:42.600 --> 00:38:44.460
The other one's up, too.

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:46.500
The flaperon goes
up on either side.

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:48.000
The rudders, you
can see how they're

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:51.350
both kind of towing
in there a little bit.

00:38:51.350 --> 00:38:52.770
The reason it's
doing that is it's

00:38:52.770 --> 00:38:55.860
trying to transfer all of
that weight from the wings

00:38:55.860 --> 00:38:56.920
and put it into the gear.

00:38:56.920 --> 00:38:59.410
So it's trying to kill all
of the lift on the wings

00:38:59.410 --> 00:39:00.960
and transfer that
to the landing gear

00:39:00.960 --> 00:39:03.780
so that you have the maximum
traction on the wheels

00:39:03.780 --> 00:39:07.640
as you hit the brakes
as you slow down.

00:39:07.640 --> 00:39:13.660
Also, on refueling-- so
when you go air refueling,

00:39:13.660 --> 00:39:16.900
there's a little switch
that you open in the jet.

00:39:16.900 --> 00:39:18.050
That opens up this door.

00:39:18.050 --> 00:39:19.510
That tells the jet
that I'm getting

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:21.480
ready to refuel
while I'm airborne.

00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:22.980
When it does that,
it says, this guy

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:25.240
isn't trying to dogfight
the airplane anymore.

00:39:25.240 --> 00:39:26.530
They're trying to get gas.

00:39:26.530 --> 00:39:29.020
So therefore I don't need
all the full roll capability

00:39:29.020 --> 00:39:30.940
and everything else, and
really, what I really

00:39:30.940 --> 00:39:32.470
want is an airplane
that's really

00:39:32.470 --> 00:39:34.070
responsive with its lift.

00:39:34.070 --> 00:39:37.720
And so, again, no input from
the pilot, but the leading edge

00:39:37.720 --> 00:39:40.630
flaps will deploy down,
the trailing edge flap

00:39:40.630 --> 00:39:42.400
and the ailerons will
also deploy down.

00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:44.820
Again, they're trying to
create camber on that wing.

00:39:44.820 --> 00:39:46.320
This is all digital
flight controls.

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:48.170
No input from the
pilot whatsoever.

00:39:48.170 --> 00:39:50.170
PROFESSOR: Laz, what would
a typical airspeed be

00:39:50.170 --> 00:39:52.390
when doing this air refueling?

00:39:52.390 --> 00:39:54.400
RANDY GORDON: This is
about-- oops, sorry.

00:39:54.400 --> 00:39:56.290
Let me go back one here.

00:39:56.290 --> 00:40:01.000
This is about 300 knots or
so, something like that.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:03.250
You've got to be able to
fly-- so for a Raptor, that's

00:40:03.250 --> 00:40:04.630
kind of slow.

00:40:04.630 --> 00:40:07.290
For the tanker airplane,
that's somewhat fast.

00:40:07.290 --> 00:40:09.130
So you're trying to
find that marriage where

00:40:09.130 --> 00:40:11.310
both airplanes have
good flying qualities

00:40:11.310 --> 00:40:13.480
so that one's not about to
stall and the other one's

00:40:13.480 --> 00:40:16.360
in full power trying
to catch up to him.

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:18.160
By the way, the
most unnatural act

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:19.870
I've ever done as
a fighter pilot

00:40:19.870 --> 00:40:22.450
is to connect up my airplane
to another airplane.

00:40:22.450 --> 00:40:23.620
I just never got used to it.

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:25.600
I can do it just fine,
but the whole notion

00:40:25.600 --> 00:40:28.720
of this big boom connecting
my airplane to a big airliner

00:40:28.720 --> 00:40:30.820
was just really strange
and weird to me.

00:40:30.820 --> 00:40:33.570
Never got used to it.

00:40:33.570 --> 00:40:34.070
OK.

00:40:34.070 --> 00:40:35.010
Some of the limiters.

00:40:35.010 --> 00:40:40.530
So in an F-15, because we talked
to that a little bit earlier,

00:40:40.530 --> 00:40:42.670
you can get up to 500,
600 miles an hour.

00:40:42.670 --> 00:40:44.220
You can take both
hands on the stick,

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:46.320
you can pull that
stick all the way back,

00:40:46.320 --> 00:40:49.080
and you will rip the wings off
the airplane and you will turn

00:40:49.080 --> 00:40:51.960
it into a big ball of metal
cascading down to the ground

00:40:51.960 --> 00:40:55.230
because you have
over-g'ed the airplane.

00:40:55.230 --> 00:40:57.660
Again, that awful, terrible
movie Top Gun in which

00:40:57.660 --> 00:41:01.120
Tom Cruise departs the
airplane and gets into a spin,

00:41:01.120 --> 00:41:03.900
again, you've exceeded some
capability of the airplane

00:41:03.900 --> 00:41:05.700
and the airplane departs
controlled flight

00:41:05.700 --> 00:41:08.310
and gets into some type
of uncontrolled situation.

00:41:08.310 --> 00:41:11.670
On a Raptor, there used to be
in the pilot operating manual

00:41:11.670 --> 00:41:14.610
a little blurb that said
quote you can maneuver

00:41:14.610 --> 00:41:18.330
this airplane with
quote reckless abandon,

00:41:18.330 --> 00:41:20.250
and you will not
over g the airplane,

00:41:20.250 --> 00:41:22.710
you will not depart the
airplane from controlled flight.

00:41:22.710 --> 00:41:27.380
They did a spectacular
job allowing this airplane

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:29.010
to get right to the
edge of performance

00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:31.530
but not going over the top.

00:41:31.530 --> 00:41:35.160
So one of the neat
things that they did--

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:36.840
airplane is in a left-hand turn.

00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:37.830
Look at that aileron.

00:41:37.830 --> 00:41:39.350
It's up.

00:41:39.350 --> 00:41:40.640
Look at that aileron.

00:41:40.640 --> 00:41:42.150
It's up.

00:41:42.150 --> 00:41:45.460
What the crap is going on there?

00:41:45.460 --> 00:41:46.960
And if you know
this one, you really

00:41:46.960 --> 00:41:50.370
do get the model
because I didn't

00:41:50.370 --> 00:41:52.860
know this for a long time.

00:41:52.860 --> 00:41:54.570
So again, just for
sake of time because I

00:41:54.570 --> 00:41:56.590
know we've got guys
coming in afterwards,

00:41:56.590 --> 00:42:00.500
center of gravity of the
airplane sits right here.

00:42:00.500 --> 00:42:02.090
In your engineering
classes you always

00:42:02.090 --> 00:42:04.820
talk about forces acting
on the center of gravity.

00:42:04.820 --> 00:42:07.070
And you take this whole
airplane and you model it down

00:42:07.070 --> 00:42:10.430
to a point mass and
you say that's--

00:42:10.430 --> 00:42:13.400
for sake of all the
sum of forces analysis.

00:42:13.400 --> 00:42:18.260
Well, in real life this
airplane's about 43 feet wide.

00:42:18.260 --> 00:42:20.340
Yeah, you can sum the
forces through there,

00:42:20.340 --> 00:42:22.670
but there's forces acting
all over this airplane

00:42:22.670 --> 00:42:24.020
at different spots.

00:42:24.020 --> 00:42:26.180
Think about here on the wingtip.

00:42:26.180 --> 00:42:28.100
I put g on the airplane.

00:42:28.100 --> 00:42:30.320
And this wing tip, it's
almost like the wings want

00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:32.900
to bend up as I'm coming down.

00:42:32.900 --> 00:42:35.420
So you put a lot of stress
out on the wing tips.

00:42:35.420 --> 00:42:37.940
So their answer,
quite ingeniously,

00:42:37.940 --> 00:42:40.040
was to deflect the
ailerons down when

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:41.360
you're at high maneuvering.

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:42.590
The way you know you're
at high maneuvering

00:42:42.590 --> 00:42:44.880
is you can kind of see these
little wispies forming off

00:42:44.880 --> 00:42:45.560
the wingtips.

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:47.510
So you are creating
low pressure.

00:42:47.510 --> 00:42:48.510
That's another one, too.

00:42:48.510 --> 00:42:51.050
You can see the clouds forming
on the front edge of the wing.

00:42:51.050 --> 00:42:53.510
Low pressure causes
that air to condense,

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:54.710
and so you make clouds.

00:42:54.710 --> 00:42:57.050
So you know the airplane's
really maneuvering up.

00:42:57.050 --> 00:43:00.020
And an answer to reduce
stress at the wingtips

00:43:00.020 --> 00:43:01.950
was to deflect the ailerons up.

00:43:01.950 --> 00:43:04.560
What happens to the lift out at
the wingtips with the ailerons

00:43:04.560 --> 00:43:06.960
up?

00:43:06.960 --> 00:43:07.670
Goes down, right?

00:43:07.670 --> 00:43:09.740
So it helps to push
those wings back

00:43:09.740 --> 00:43:12.920
down again so you're not trying
to overstress the airplane.

00:43:12.920 --> 00:43:15.560
There are limiters like
this all over the airplane,

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:18.130
such that you won't
over g the airplane.

00:43:18.130 --> 00:43:20.510
Literally, you can do anything
you want to this airplane.

00:43:20.510 --> 00:43:23.420
That's what I'm telling you,
it's easier to fly a Raptor

00:43:23.420 --> 00:43:25.790
than it is to fly a
Cessna because you really

00:43:25.790 --> 00:43:27.380
have to pay attention to what
you're doing in a Cessna.

00:43:27.380 --> 00:43:29.060
In a Raptor, I could
put my kid in there

00:43:29.060 --> 00:43:31.610
and he can do this all day at
whatever speed, and nothing bad

00:43:31.610 --> 00:43:32.770
will happen to the airplane.

00:43:32.770 --> 00:43:36.480
It's really quite spectacular
how they did that.

00:43:36.480 --> 00:43:37.860
The other part
I'll give you here

00:43:37.860 --> 00:43:39.470
is some of the command systems.

00:43:39.470 --> 00:43:42.970
So if I'm in a dogfight and I'm
trying to shoot the other guy,

00:43:42.970 --> 00:43:46.160
I'm going against a
maneuvering target.

00:43:46.160 --> 00:43:48.310
And so the flight
controls transfer over

00:43:48.310 --> 00:43:50.950
to what's called a
g command system.

00:43:50.950 --> 00:43:53.560
So if I'm maneuvering at 4
g's and I let go of the stick,

00:43:53.560 --> 00:43:54.890
the airplane will stay at 4 g's.

00:43:54.890 --> 00:43:57.100
And if I see that the target's
maneuvering and I need

00:43:57.100 --> 00:43:58.960
to go to 6 g's or 7
g's, I'll put that in

00:43:58.960 --> 00:44:00.300
and the airplane will keep that.

00:44:00.300 --> 00:44:02.860
So in other words,
again, it's a vote.

00:44:02.860 --> 00:44:04.760
I'm not physically
connected to anything.

00:44:04.760 --> 00:44:07.240
I talk to the computer
and I say, I want 6 g's.

00:44:07.240 --> 00:44:09.850
And the airplane does all types
of black magic and sorcery

00:44:09.850 --> 00:44:13.210
behind me, and Lo and behold,
the airplane gets to 6 to 7

00:44:13.210 --> 00:44:13.820
g's.

00:44:13.820 --> 00:44:16.030
That really matters when
you're in a high maneuvering

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:18.910
kind of situation,
so it goes g command.

00:44:18.910 --> 00:44:21.920
When you're slower,
i.e. on landing,

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:25.210
and I want to put that flight
path marker right on that edge

00:44:25.210 --> 00:44:27.550
of the runway because that's
where I want to touch down,

00:44:27.550 --> 00:44:31.700
right at the 1,000-foot
markers, then in that scenario,

00:44:31.700 --> 00:44:33.850
I'm not really caring
so much about g command,

00:44:33.850 --> 00:44:35.360
I care about pitch rate.

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:37.870
And so it transitions over
to a pitch rate command.

00:44:37.870 --> 00:44:39.880
And if I put no
input on the stick,

00:44:39.880 --> 00:44:43.240
it says zero pitch rate,
again, black magic and sorcery

00:44:43.240 --> 00:44:44.170
will happen behind me.

00:44:44.170 --> 00:44:45.280
The flight controls
will do whatever

00:44:45.280 --> 00:44:47.800
they need to do to make sure
that my pitch rate stays

00:44:47.800 --> 00:44:48.760
at zero.

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:51.100
So it transitions from one
type of light control system

00:44:51.100 --> 00:44:51.640
to the other.

00:44:51.640 --> 00:44:53.150
No pilot input whatsoever.

00:44:53.150 --> 00:44:57.310
It's just based off of
flight command system.

00:44:57.310 --> 00:44:57.810
All right.

