something different.

00:50:32.750 --> 00:50:35.420
One of my good friends,
test pilot, outstanding guy.

00:50:35.420 --> 00:50:37.230
So don't think of this
as he's a bad pilot.

00:50:37.230 --> 00:50:39.300
He's not, he's awesome.

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:41.990
But the jet believes
something that

00:50:41.990 --> 00:50:44.390
wasn't really true because
there was an error in how

00:50:44.390 --> 00:50:46.130
the software was coded.

00:50:46.130 --> 00:50:48.950
And you'll see the
first approach--

00:50:48.950 --> 00:50:51.210
he'll take off again on
what's called military power,

00:50:51.210 --> 00:50:53.030
so they're not
using afterburner,

00:50:53.030 --> 00:50:55.610
and the airplane
behaves just fine.

00:50:55.610 --> 00:50:58.630
The next time around, he goes
around using afterburner power,

00:50:58.630 --> 00:51:01.130
so you'll see fire come out of
the back end of the airplane.

00:51:01.130 --> 00:51:03.860
And that changes something
in the flight system

00:51:03.860 --> 00:51:06.410
for the engines, which
tells the flight control

00:51:06.410 --> 00:51:08.570
computer a different condition.

00:51:08.570 --> 00:51:11.580
And what ended up happening is
that the gains, if you will,

00:51:11.580 --> 00:51:14.420
of the stick were
completely off.

00:51:14.420 --> 00:51:16.880
So again, this would be like
if you were on a highway speed

00:51:16.880 --> 00:51:18.540
and that same wheel
deflection you would

00:51:18.540 --> 00:51:20.480
use to park your car
in your garage, now

00:51:20.480 --> 00:51:22.280
that little deflection
of your wheel

00:51:22.280 --> 00:51:24.710
makes that same turn
of the tires up front.

00:51:24.710 --> 00:51:29.060
So you get into what's called a
pilot-induced oscillation, PIO,

00:51:29.060 --> 00:51:31.520
which basically says you're
out of phase with the airplane.

00:51:31.520 --> 00:51:33.930
If I'm driving my car and I
turn the steering wheel right,

00:51:33.930 --> 00:51:35.090
the car is going left.

00:51:35.090 --> 00:51:37.010
As it's going left, I'm
trying to correct, I go right,

00:51:37.010 --> 00:51:38.240
and now the thing goes right.

00:51:38.240 --> 00:51:40.280
And so you get out of
phase with the airplane,

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:41.440
and you'll see what happens.

00:51:41.440 --> 00:51:42.440
Go ahead and play.

00:51:42.440 --> 00:51:43.970
By the way, you see all
the flight control surfaces

00:51:43.970 --> 00:51:45.200
deflecting in the back?

00:51:45.200 --> 00:51:46.860
This is now in a
pitch rate system.

00:51:46.860 --> 00:51:48.560
So he's just trying
to land the airplane.

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:50.150
The back of the
airplane does whatever

00:51:50.150 --> 00:51:52.550
it needs to do to keep that
flight path marker exactly

00:51:52.550 --> 00:51:53.420
where it needs to go.

00:51:57.650 --> 00:51:59.950
And again, all the flight
control surface is deflected.

00:51:59.950 --> 00:52:02.650
Military power because the
engines are black, if you will,

00:52:02.650 --> 00:52:03.320
on this one.

00:52:03.320 --> 00:52:04.780
On the next time
around, you'll see

00:52:04.780 --> 00:52:07.630
him maneuver with
afterburner, and you'll

00:52:07.630 --> 00:52:10.020
see him get into this
pitch-induced oscillation.

00:52:18.210 --> 00:52:19.800
That's the chase
airplane, by the way.

00:52:19.800 --> 00:52:21.470
It's an F-16 that
follows them around.

00:52:29.300 --> 00:52:31.030
So same thing, getting
set up to land.

00:52:31.030 --> 00:52:33.100
The camera goes out of
focus here for a second,

00:52:33.100 --> 00:52:34.240
comes back in.

00:52:34.240 --> 00:52:35.740
Again, just notice
everything that's

00:52:35.740 --> 00:52:37.620
happening on the back
end of this airplane

00:52:37.620 --> 00:52:40.120
to keep that pitch rate where
the pilot has commanded it to.

00:52:44.950 --> 00:52:46.120
Two things will happen here.

00:52:46.120 --> 00:52:48.030
He selects afterburner
and he raises the gear.

00:52:48.030 --> 00:52:50.050
That changes the
flight control laws.

00:52:50.050 --> 00:52:53.290
And the gains were
not set correctly.

00:52:53.290 --> 00:52:54.290
There's the afterburner.

00:52:54.290 --> 00:52:57.900
And now you see where he's out
of phase with the airplane.

00:52:57.900 --> 00:53:00.360
And he's doing everything to
keep the airplane from hitting

00:53:00.360 --> 00:53:02.130
the ground, and can't avoid it.

00:53:04.670 --> 00:53:09.500
He's OK, but the airplane
was fairly well scraped,

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:10.920
as you can imagine.

00:53:10.920 --> 00:53:12.350
So it's just a danger.

00:53:12.350 --> 00:53:14.270
The digital flight
controls allow a lot

00:53:14.270 --> 00:53:16.370
of flexibility and creativity.

00:53:16.370 --> 00:53:18.950
There used to be a term,
eh, it's only software,

00:53:18.950 --> 00:53:20.040
we can figure it out.

00:53:20.040 --> 00:53:24.860
Not true when you're dealing
with vehicles like this,

00:53:24.860 --> 00:53:26.500
where small changes
in software code

00:53:26.500 --> 00:53:29.090
can have dramatic implications
on the ability of the airplane.

00:53:29.090 --> 00:53:32.140
So it takes an
amazing amount of--

00:53:32.140 --> 00:53:32.810
PROFESSOR: Demo?

00:53:32.810 --> 00:53:34.070
RANDY GORDON: Yeah, you can
go ahead and do Raptor demo.

00:53:34.070 --> 00:53:35.480
And with that, we
can go questions

00:53:35.480 --> 00:53:37.340
because I'm a little bit over.

00:53:37.340 --> 00:53:38.390
PROFESSOR: No, it's fine.

00:53:38.390 --> 00:53:40.190
RANDY GORDON: OK.

00:53:40.190 --> 00:53:42.920
So we can play this full
screen, if you will.

00:53:46.320 --> 00:53:48.700
PROFESSOR: You want to take
questions while it's running?

00:53:48.700 --> 00:53:48.940
RANDY GORDON: Yeah.

00:53:48.940 --> 00:53:50.350
So this is from
another good buddy

00:53:50.350 --> 00:53:52.190
of mine, a guy
name Zeke Skalicky,

00:53:52.190 --> 00:53:53.550
who was the Raptor demo pilot.

00:53:53.550 --> 00:53:54.890
Outstanding guy.

00:53:54.890 --> 00:53:57.060
But this is the Raptor demo
if you've never seen it.

00:53:57.060 --> 00:53:59.100
So we'll take some questions
while this is going.

00:53:59.100 --> 00:54:00.060
Go ahead.

00:54:00.060 --> 00:54:02.580
AUDIENCE: Is there a thrust
to weight ratio on an F-22?

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:04.410
RANDY GORDON: Yeah,
greater than one to one.

00:54:04.410 --> 00:54:07.860
So the airplane, about
63,000, 64,000 pounds.

00:54:07.860 --> 00:54:09.630
Normally a strong takeoff.

00:54:09.630 --> 00:54:13.060
The thrust coming out the
back is 70,000 pounds.

00:54:13.060 --> 00:54:14.700
So on a nice cold
day, like if you're

00:54:14.700 --> 00:54:17.670
close enough to sea level,
you will actually go faster

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:21.000
than the speed of sound
while you're climbing up,

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:23.360
which is cool.

00:54:23.360 --> 00:54:23.860
Yeah?

00:54:23.860 --> 00:54:27.350
AUDIENCE: What is the thrust
vectoring while taking off?

00:54:27.350 --> 00:54:29.090
PROFESSOR: Laz, try to--

00:54:29.090 --> 00:54:29.590
oh, yeah.

00:54:29.590 --> 00:54:31.090
Try to repeat the
question if you can.

00:54:31.090 --> 00:54:32.090
RANDY GORDON: Oh, sorry.

00:54:32.090 --> 00:54:33.640
PROFESSOR: Because
he's not mic'ed.

00:54:33.640 --> 00:54:34.990
RANDY GORDON: So
the question was--

00:54:34.990 --> 00:54:37.150
well, one, the question was
the thrust to weight ratio.

00:54:37.150 --> 00:54:39.270
It's greater than one to
one-- a little bit greater

00:54:39.270 --> 00:54:40.900
than one to one on takeoff.

00:54:40.900 --> 00:54:43.070
By the way, watch this
maneuver here real quick.

00:54:43.070 --> 00:54:45.750
So that's the thrust
vectoring kicking

00:54:45.750 --> 00:54:48.340
in to really get the airplane--
so initially it has the flight

00:54:48.340 --> 00:54:49.160
control surfaces.

00:54:49.160 --> 00:54:51.250
And then as things slow
down, the thrust vectoring

00:54:51.250 --> 00:54:55.990
kicks in to basically turn the
airplane into a flat plate.

00:54:55.990 --> 00:54:58.830
Second question was about the
thrust vectoring on takeoff.

00:54:58.830 --> 00:55:01.460
So it'll put it a little bit up,
not much, just a little bit up

00:55:01.460 --> 00:55:05.540
to help the nose
rotate just a tad.

00:55:05.540 --> 00:55:08.220
This is that high angle of
attack maneuver, if you will.

00:55:12.580 --> 00:55:13.080
Keep going.

00:55:13.080 --> 00:55:15.090
It's all good questions.

00:55:15.090 --> 00:55:15.590
Yeah?

00:55:15.590 --> 00:55:17.920
AUDIENCE: You said all the
software is written basically

00:55:17.920 --> 00:55:19.750
so the plane can't
damage itself.

00:55:19.750 --> 00:55:21.110
Does the pilot become a limiter?

00:55:21.110 --> 00:55:23.550
Can it put you in situations
where it can hurt you?

00:55:23.550 --> 00:55:24.930
RANDY GORDON:
Yeah, very much so.

00:55:24.930 --> 00:55:27.050
In fact, we've kind of
achieved that spot now,

00:55:27.050 --> 00:55:28.850
where the pilot very
much is limiting

00:55:28.850 --> 00:55:31.310
the performance of the airplane
itself because the airplane

00:55:31.310 --> 00:55:33.540
could do so much more.

00:55:33.540 --> 00:55:36.110
So this is what's called a
fifth generation fighter.

00:55:36.110 --> 00:55:40.180
The first generation was like
an old Korean War, like F-86

00:55:40.180 --> 00:55:40.890
kind of airplane.

00:55:40.890 --> 00:55:43.130
And then successively
through the generations,

00:55:43.130 --> 00:55:44.720
you arrive at this
fifth generation,

00:55:44.720 --> 00:55:46.760
which to me is the
pinnacle of what

00:55:46.760 --> 00:55:50.480
you could get with a human
and an airplane together.

00:55:50.480 --> 00:55:53.840
Sixth generation is going to
involve teaming this airplane

00:55:53.840 --> 00:55:56.910
with unmanned airplanes,
and the unmanned airplanes

00:55:56.910 --> 00:55:59.330
are going to have a lot more
capability from a maneuvering

00:55:59.330 --> 00:56:00.740
standpoint because
they don't have

00:56:00.740 --> 00:56:02.580
the limitation of the
pilot and all the life

00:56:02.580 --> 00:56:04.830
support systems that come
with it and everything else.

00:56:04.830 --> 00:56:07.130
So all that weight you would
normally devote to that,

00:56:07.130 --> 00:56:09.300
you can get away with
putting other stuff in there.

00:56:09.300 --> 00:56:11.600
When I was telling you it
flies at about the same speed

00:56:11.600 --> 00:56:13.200
as a Cessna--

00:56:13.200 --> 00:56:14.870
I mean, this is those
types of maneuvers

00:56:14.870 --> 00:56:15.890
there where you can
get away with that.

00:56:15.890 --> 00:56:18.050
Again, watch the flight
control surfaces in the back

00:56:18.050 --> 00:56:20.950
and what's going on.

00:56:20.950 --> 00:56:23.350
Later on they'll do a pass
where he'll open up the doors

00:56:23.350 --> 00:56:24.940
and you can see the main
weapon bay, which is

00:56:24.940 --> 00:56:26.230
underneath the airplane belly.

00:56:26.230 --> 00:56:28.390
And then you'll see the
side weapon bay doors,

00:56:28.390 --> 00:56:30.390
so you can kind of see
where all the weapons are

00:56:30.390 --> 00:56:31.660
carried inside the airplane.

00:56:31.660 --> 00:56:34.070
Again, a huge center
of gravity challenge.

00:56:34.070 --> 00:56:35.320
So here's that maneuver there.

00:56:35.320 --> 00:56:36.440
You can see the doors open.

00:56:39.220 --> 00:56:40.890
One thing I didn't
really tell you about

00:56:40.890 --> 00:56:43.250
is, so in that such
situation, because missiles

00:56:43.250 --> 00:56:45.840
weigh a couple hundred pounds a
piece or so, some of the bombs

00:56:45.840 --> 00:56:48.120
are about 1,000 pounds apiece,
when you lose all that weight

00:56:48.120 --> 00:56:49.820
immediately, it's
literally like dropping

00:56:49.820 --> 00:56:51.990
a car off the front
end of your airplane.

00:56:51.990 --> 00:56:54.210
The way that it fixes that
center of gravity issue

00:56:54.210 --> 00:56:56.380
is by changing fuel
inside the airplane.

00:56:56.380 --> 00:56:58.470
So it sloshes fuel
forward or back

00:56:58.470 --> 00:56:59.910
to keep the center of gravity.

00:56:59.910 --> 00:57:02.310
Again, there's no
fuel control panel

00:57:02.310 --> 00:57:04.650
where I go, well, move this
and click this and whatever.

00:57:04.650 --> 00:57:06.310
It does it all
completely automatically.

00:57:06.310 --> 00:57:07.020
Go ahead.

00:57:07.020 --> 00:57:08.600
AUDIENCE: What kind
of sensors can you

00:57:08.600 --> 00:57:10.830
use to detect the
center of gravity?

00:57:10.830 --> 00:57:12.630
RANDY GORDON: The
sensors that you can use?

00:57:12.630 --> 00:57:15.810
So all of the fuel
tanks are instrumented,

00:57:15.810 --> 00:57:17.820
so you know the status
of fuel in terms

00:57:17.820 --> 00:57:20.070
of where things are set up.

00:57:20.070 --> 00:57:22.220
You tell it-- well,
actually, it has the ability

00:57:22.220 --> 00:57:23.520
to know what's on the airplane.

00:57:23.520 --> 00:57:25.020
So when you load a
missile, it goes,

00:57:25.020 --> 00:57:27.480
oh, it's this type of missile
and it weighs this much,

00:57:27.480 --> 00:57:29.070
and it knows the
mass properties of it

00:57:29.070 --> 00:57:31.940
and so it sets it up from there.

00:57:31.940 --> 00:57:33.350
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:33.350 --> 00:57:37.220
RANDY GORDON: So it actually
identifies that all by itself.

00:57:37.220 --> 00:57:40.210
So like in a Cirrus, you
have to actually pull up

00:57:40.210 --> 00:57:42.610
a screen in the Cirrus and
go, my passenger weighs this

00:57:42.610 --> 00:57:44.340
and I've got this
baggage on board,

00:57:44.340 --> 00:57:46.090
and then it gives you
the picture of where

00:57:46.090 --> 00:57:47.300
the center of gravity is.

00:57:47.300 --> 00:57:48.850
This thing, because
it's all digital,

00:57:48.850 --> 00:57:51.140
the missile has a little
connector rod that connects it

00:57:51.140 --> 00:57:53.040
and it says, behold,
I'm a missile.

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:54.180
AUDIENCE: What about
the pilot weight?

00:57:54.180 --> 00:57:55.630
RANDY GORDON: Oh,
the pilot weight?

00:57:55.630 --> 00:57:58.900
Doesn't matter because
they spec'ed it--

00:57:58.900 --> 00:58:01.900
well, it matters but
for a different reason.

00:58:01.900 --> 00:58:04.330
It matters for the ejection
seat, predominantly.

00:58:04.330 --> 00:58:06.520
Because the ejection seat--

00:58:06.520 --> 00:58:09.190
I think it's like 135
pounds is the lightest,

00:58:09.190 --> 00:58:13.420
something like that, 115 to
135 to, like, 220 or something.

00:58:13.420 --> 00:58:15.120
It's something around that spot.

00:58:15.120 --> 00:58:17.620
So to be able to be within the
safe envelope of the ejection

00:58:17.620 --> 00:58:21.430
seat, that's where the
weight of the pilot matters.

00:58:21.430 --> 00:58:23.800
But they spec the center
of gravity such that

00:58:23.800 --> 00:58:26.320
so long as really
anyone can sit up front

00:58:26.320 --> 00:58:28.700
and you're not going to throw
off the CG of the airplane,

00:58:28.700 --> 00:58:31.300
even though you're way
far forward of the CG

00:58:31.300 --> 00:58:33.010
and there's a moment arm there.

00:58:33.010 --> 00:58:34.810
But between everything
else in the cockpit,

00:58:34.810 --> 00:58:37.240
that ejection seat is
ridiculously heavy.

00:58:37.240 --> 00:58:39.900
And all the avionics that sit
up front, the radars up front,

00:58:39.900 --> 00:58:41.320
all these things
that sit up there

00:58:41.320 --> 00:58:43.650
have far more of a contribution
to the center of gravity

00:58:43.650 --> 00:58:47.380
than you do, unless you're,
like, Shaq or something

00:58:47.380 --> 00:58:47.880
like that.

00:58:47.880 --> 00:58:48.910
But go ahead.

00:58:48.910 --> 00:58:54.790
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
on the helmet screen?

00:58:54.790 --> 00:58:56.910
RANDY GORDON: So in
this airplane, not yet.

00:58:56.910 --> 00:58:57.960
That's coming along soon.

00:58:57.960 --> 00:59:00.370
Some of the older airplanes,
believe it or not, have that.

00:59:00.370 --> 00:59:03.330
Like the F-15 that I flew,
you had a special helmet

00:59:03.330 --> 00:59:07.410
that had all of the information
displayed on the visor itself.

00:59:07.410 --> 00:59:09.960
So in addition to that hands-on
throttle and stick so I don't

00:59:09.960 --> 00:59:11.500
have to take my
hands off of anything

00:59:11.500 --> 00:59:13.170
to touch anything
in the cockpit,

00:59:13.170 --> 00:59:15.090
I also don't have to
look in the cockpit

00:59:15.090 --> 00:59:18.470
to see altitude,
air speed, heading.

00:59:18.470 --> 00:59:21.600
It's all displayed
to me upfront.

00:59:21.600 --> 00:59:24.700
This airplane eventually
will get that.

00:59:24.700 --> 00:59:27.120
This is a programmatic
discussion now.

00:59:27.120 --> 00:59:29.370
They only had so many dollars
to spend, and they said,

00:59:29.370 --> 00:59:31.830
this airplane is so
awesome that it shouldn't

00:59:31.830 --> 00:59:34.080
need a helmet-mounted display
system because it should

00:59:34.080 --> 00:59:36.930
be able to see all the bad
guys from far enough away

00:59:36.930 --> 00:59:38.460
and not be a problem.

00:59:38.460 --> 00:59:41.170
We fielded the
airplane that way.

00:59:41.170 --> 00:59:42.630
The first batch of
pilots, they all

00:59:42.630 --> 00:59:46.210
transitioned from airplanes that
had that helmet-mounted system.

00:59:46.210 --> 00:59:48.510
And they came to this airplane
where it didn't have it,

00:59:48.510 --> 00:59:49.540
and they were pissed.

00:59:49.540 --> 00:59:51.600
They were like, we've
got to have that back.

00:59:51.600 --> 00:59:53.430
So that's kind of where
a lot of the efforts

00:59:53.430 --> 00:59:55.910
now are going to modernize
the airplane a bit.

00:59:55.910 --> 00:59:56.420
What else?

00:59:56.420 --> 00:59:57.040
Good questions.

00:59:57.040 --> 00:59:57.630
Go ahead.

00:59:57.630 --> 00:59:58.200
Yeah?

00:59:58.200 --> 01:00:00.540
AUDIENCE: Why is there a need
for humans in the cockpit?

01:00:00.540 --> 01:00:02.810
Why not just go for
unmanned systems?

01:00:02.810 --> 01:00:06.760
RANDY GORDON: Yeah, it is the
great debate of the fighter

01:00:06.760 --> 01:00:07.780
community right now.

01:00:07.780 --> 01:00:10.120
You're really touching on
something really, really deep.

01:00:12.800 --> 01:00:15.930
The best answer so far
is that the greatest--

01:00:15.930 --> 01:00:18.350
I mean, we talked a lot about
the hardware and the systems

01:00:18.350 --> 01:00:19.310
on board the airplane.

01:00:19.310 --> 01:00:21.710
Really, the greatest piece
of capability on the airplane

01:00:21.710 --> 01:00:25.990
is the mind of the
person flying up front.

01:00:25.990 --> 01:00:29.120
If it's a very dynamic
and changing environment,

01:00:29.120 --> 01:00:31.820
to be able to tell a machine
to be able to incorporate all

01:00:31.820 --> 01:00:35.090
those inputs and make the
right decisions based on that,

01:00:35.090 --> 01:00:36.350
kind of hard to do right now.

01:00:36.350 --> 01:00:38.850
I'm not saying we're not going
to get there, just right now,

01:00:38.850 --> 01:00:39.790
it's difficult.

01:00:39.790 --> 01:00:41.510
Where we use unmanned
systems a lot

01:00:41.510 --> 01:00:44.080
now is in surveillance
missions, where

01:00:44.080 --> 01:00:45.330
you can just launch the thing.

01:00:45.330 --> 01:00:47.090
And it's got a
pre-programmed navigation,

01:00:47.090 --> 01:00:49.940
and it knows what it needs to
do and it can set things up.

01:00:49.940 --> 01:00:52.340
Those are somewhat
bounded problems,

01:00:52.340 --> 01:00:54.200
is probably the best
way to describe it,

01:00:54.200 --> 01:00:56.450
where you could use an
unmanned system for that.

01:00:56.450 --> 01:00:58.790
Where it gets difficulties
is in combat situation,

01:00:58.790 --> 01:01:00.230
it's extremely dynamic.

01:01:00.230 --> 01:01:04.100
It's battle royale,
WWF, mosh pit,

01:01:04.100 --> 01:01:06.110
any possible chaotic
situation you can put,

01:01:06.110 --> 01:01:08.130
that's kind of
what it looks like.

01:01:08.130 --> 01:01:10.700
And so having a human mind
attached in that environment,

01:01:10.700 --> 01:01:12.990
to be able to adapt and do
what the mind does better

01:01:12.990 --> 01:01:14.660
than a machine does,
at least right now,

01:01:14.660 --> 01:01:20.600
that's the main argument to keep
humans in the system for now.

01:01:20.600 --> 01:01:21.830
Yeah?

01:01:21.830 --> 01:01:24.540
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] operate
these planes [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:24.540 --> 01:01:28.630
to remotely operate
them, is the [INAUDIBLE]??

01:01:28.630 --> 01:01:30.170
RANDY GORDON: It is.

01:01:30.170 --> 01:01:31.930
PROFESSOR: Can you
repeat the question?

01:01:31.930 --> 01:01:34.470
RANDY GORDON: Yeah, the question
is that if you operate these

01:01:34.470 --> 01:01:37.180
things remotely--
so even if you had--

01:01:37.180 --> 01:01:40.170
classic example, we'll
use Sully Sullenberger

01:01:40.170 --> 01:01:42.760
because we talked about
Sully in the previous one.

01:01:42.760 --> 01:01:45.280
You take off out of LaGuardia,
you lose both engines.

01:01:45.280 --> 01:01:48.550
If you could have a remote pilot
sitting somewhere else that

01:01:48.550 --> 01:01:50.590
could take over and
decide land on the Hudson,

01:01:50.590 --> 01:01:53.850
because a machine most likely
wouldn't have made that choice,

01:01:53.850 --> 01:01:55.390
is there a time lag issue?

01:01:55.390 --> 01:01:57.430
The answer is 100% yes.

01:01:57.430 --> 01:01:59.450
There is a time lag
issue between getting

01:01:59.450 --> 01:02:01.450
that information displayed
down, make the input,

01:02:01.450 --> 01:02:04.450
that input goes back
up and comes back over.

01:02:04.450 --> 01:02:07.930
A thing we've done at
test pilot school is--

01:02:07.930 --> 01:02:10.870
remember we showed earlier
that flight path marker,

01:02:10.870 --> 01:02:12.860
where as a pilot you put
the flight path marker

01:02:12.860 --> 01:02:15.070
and that's exactly where
your airplane's going to go?

01:02:15.070 --> 01:02:17.560
If there's a time lag, that
will actually mess you up

01:02:17.560 --> 01:02:19.930
because there's some second
or two delay between what

01:02:19.930 --> 01:02:21.920
you're seeing and what the
airplane's actually going.

01:02:21.920 --> 01:02:23.370
At test pilot
school, they actually

01:02:23.370 --> 01:02:27.820
built a flight path marker that
accounts for that time delay.

01:02:27.820 --> 01:02:30.280
If it knows that time delay,
it will actually count for it.

01:02:30.280 --> 01:02:34.330
So you could fly the airplane
remotely even with the time lag

01:02:34.330 --> 01:02:36.680
and still be able to do very
high gain tasks, like land

01:02:36.680 --> 01:02:38.350
the airplane, for
instance, where things

01:02:38.350 --> 01:02:39.460
are changing very rapidly.

01:02:39.460 --> 01:02:42.140
So it's a new science, not
fully fleshed out here.

01:02:42.140 --> 01:02:43.720
But the proof of
concept has been

01:02:43.720 --> 01:02:47.920
demonstrated, to control
an airplane remotely even

01:02:47.920 --> 01:02:49.390
with the time lag.

01:02:49.390 --> 01:02:51.040
Who really cares
about that right now

01:02:51.040 --> 01:02:54.170
are the airlines because,
to be very frank,

01:02:54.170 --> 01:02:56.470
the pilots tend to be a pain
in the butt for an airline

01:02:56.470 --> 01:02:57.460
company.

01:02:57.460 --> 01:02:59.170
And if you can remove
the pilots and just

01:02:59.170 --> 01:03:02.860
have a remote operated system
or even an autonomous system,

01:03:02.860 --> 01:03:04.990
from a business
standpoint, the company

01:03:04.990 --> 01:03:06.960
really likes that from
an aviation standpoint.

01:03:06.960 --> 01:03:08.860
It triggers all
types of discussions

01:03:08.860 --> 01:03:11.480
in a lot of other issues,
but that's one question.

01:03:11.480 --> 01:03:11.980
Go ahead.

01:03:11.980 --> 01:03:14.290
PROFESSOR: Let me jump in
for a minute with that.

01:03:14.290 --> 01:03:18.310
I think actually to me, one of
the holy grails of GA safety

01:03:18.310 --> 01:03:24.430
would be to have a
human co-pilot, perhaps,

01:03:24.430 --> 01:03:25.570
on the ground.

01:03:25.570 --> 01:03:27.070
So if you had that
kind of telemetry

01:03:27.070 --> 01:03:31.850
that you have in a drone, a
human somewhere else could say,

01:03:31.850 --> 01:03:33.400
you're running a
little short on fuel

01:03:33.400 --> 01:03:35.270
or you forgot to change
tanks, all the things

01:03:35.270 --> 01:03:38.530
that a human co-pilot could
do right in the cockpit.

01:03:38.530 --> 01:03:40.270
Most of that safety
running checklist

01:03:40.270 --> 01:03:43.270
could be probably
enhanced remotely.

01:03:43.270 --> 01:03:46.240
So that would be a great add
to a Cessna, or a Piper, even.

01:03:46.240 --> 01:03:47.830
RANDY GORDON: And
you see a little bit

01:03:47.830 --> 01:03:49.240
now in some of the more
advanced airplanes,

01:03:49.240 --> 01:03:50.230
like we talked a
little bit about if I

01:03:50.230 --> 01:03:52.720
have an engine problem in the
Raptor, I literally do nothing.

01:03:52.720 --> 01:03:53.980
I just sit there and
stare at the clouds

01:03:53.980 --> 01:03:56.080
and go, wow, what a lovely
day, and the computer

01:03:56.080 --> 01:03:58.120
fixes it for me.

01:03:58.120 --> 01:04:00.500
There are other scenarios
where the jet will tell me,

01:04:00.500 --> 01:04:01.960
hey, you've got a
generator problem

01:04:01.960 --> 01:04:05.260
and then immediately pull up
the checklist for the generator

01:04:05.260 --> 01:04:07.070
failure to allow me to fix it.

01:04:07.070 --> 01:04:10.540
So you see some basic automation
right now already in play.

01:04:10.540 --> 01:04:11.590
A couple other questions.

01:04:11.590 --> 01:04:12.710
I know we're running short.

01:04:12.710 --> 01:04:14.390
Go ahead.

01:04:14.390 --> 01:04:16.810
AUDIENCE: How much of flying
a Raptor is seat of the pants

01:04:16.810 --> 01:04:19.540
that you would miss by
not being in the cockpit?

01:04:19.540 --> 01:04:20.920
RANDY GORDON: By
not being there?

01:04:20.920 --> 01:04:22.310
AUDIENCE: Or is it so automated
at this point that it's

01:04:22.310 --> 01:04:25.070
the same whether you're sitting
there or at a computer screen?

01:04:25.070 --> 01:04:26.770
RANDY GORDON: Yeah, if it's a--

01:04:26.770 --> 01:04:28.090
so we have two terms.

01:04:28.090 --> 01:04:29.890
One is called beyond
visual range, which

01:04:29.890 --> 01:04:32.529
means I can't see the
other guy with my eyes,

01:04:32.529 --> 01:04:34.930
but my sensors can see him.

01:04:34.930 --> 01:04:37.540
And if I'm shooting missiles
long distance like that,

01:04:37.540 --> 01:04:40.330
I don't lose any seat of
the pants by being remotely.

01:04:40.330 --> 01:04:41.290
It's like a video game.

01:04:41.290 --> 01:04:43.460
Literally, it's exactly
like a video game.

01:04:43.460 --> 01:04:45.670
If it's a maneuvering
environment where I see the guy

01:04:45.670 --> 01:04:47.120
and we're in a
dogfight, then yeah,

01:04:47.120 --> 01:04:49.540
you lose a lot in terms
of seat of the pants,

01:04:49.540 --> 01:04:52.120
eyeball, just things that
are hard to automate.

01:04:52.120 --> 01:04:54.250
So it's half and half.

01:04:54.250 --> 01:04:57.550
In a drone scenario,
would a drone dogfight?

01:04:57.550 --> 01:04:58.100
I don't know.

01:04:58.100 --> 01:04:58.970
It's a good question.

01:04:58.970 --> 01:05:00.279
I'm not really sure.

01:05:00.279 --> 01:05:03.190
Go ahead.

01:05:03.190 --> 01:05:06.980
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:05:06.980 --> 01:05:08.529
RANDY GORDON: You
could, but then I'd

01:05:08.529 --> 01:05:10.300
have to have some
way to represent

01:05:10.300 --> 01:05:12.470
the physical environment
that the drone is seeing.

01:05:12.470 --> 01:05:14.010
I've got to be able
to represent that

01:05:14.010 --> 01:05:16.620
to the guy in the
simulator on the ground.

01:05:16.620 --> 01:05:19.310
I have to be able to
relay that real time.

01:05:19.310 --> 01:05:19.810
It matters.

01:05:19.810 --> 01:05:23.450
So who play sports?

01:05:23.450 --> 01:05:24.980
Guys, any of you?

01:05:24.980 --> 01:05:27.779
Whenever you're playing
sports, you've got an opponent.

01:05:27.779 --> 01:05:30.200
If you play it a lot, like if
it's racquetball or football

01:05:30.200 --> 01:05:31.220
or something like
that, you get very

01:05:31.220 --> 01:05:32.970
good at looking at
your opponent and being

01:05:32.970 --> 01:05:36.200
able to see micro movements
before the actual big movement

01:05:36.200 --> 01:05:39.090
happens, so that you know, oh,
they're about to swing this way

01:05:39.090 --> 01:05:40.540
or they're going
to throw this way.

01:05:40.540 --> 01:05:43.010
So you can read your
opponent and make a decision

01:05:43.010 --> 01:05:45.730
about what's about to happen
a second or two from now.

01:05:45.730 --> 01:05:47.720
In a fighter jet,
the exact same thing.

01:05:47.720 --> 01:05:51.830
If I'm fighting a guy and I see
a control surface deflection,

01:05:51.830 --> 01:05:53.420
even before the
airplane is gone,

01:05:53.420 --> 01:05:56.310
I know the person
is going this way,

01:05:56.310 --> 01:05:59.420
I can position myself to be
there before they arrive.

01:05:59.420 --> 01:06:01.520
I would need some way
to represent that if I'm

01:06:01.520 --> 01:06:03.260
in a simulator on
the ground, and it

01:06:03.260 --> 01:06:07.250
would have to be transparent to
the guy in the simulator what

01:06:07.250 --> 01:06:08.710
that feels like.

